faq.components.title: Components
faq.howto.create_scenario.details:
OpenAEV is a toolbox, you can create and tailor a scenario to your needs. To do so, from the scenario page,  you can create a new scenario, add existing injects based on the current payload library. 
If you need more customization you also have the possibility to create your custom payload from the payload page and add it to your scenario.
faq.howto.create_scenario.summary: How do I create my own scenario ?
faq.howto.import_scenario.details: You can import a scenario from the scenario page by clicking on the import icon on the top right of the page. You can also deploy in one click our library of scenario directly from our [XTM Hub library](https://hub.filigran.io/cybersecurity-solutions/open-bas-scenarios)
faq.howto.run_scenario.details:
From a scenario, you can choose to run a scenario directly by clicking on “launch” or you can choose to schedule for a one time run or a recurrent run in order to continuously test your environment on a scenario. 

Each Launch of a scenario will instantiate a new **simulation** where you will be able to track the progression and access the result of the simulation.
faq.howto.understand_results.details: You can look at your assessments results at different level:
faq.howto.understand_results.home_dashbo: **Home dashboard and custom dashboard**: They give you global metrics about your platform, aggregating data from all performed assessments.
faq.howto.understand_results.inject_resu: **Inject results**: This is the most granular level of information you can get, at this level you will find execution logs, expectations results by target, links to Security system alerts detected and remediation recommendation.
faq.howto.understand_results.scenario.de: **Scenario**: you can find here aggregated data of all simulations instantiated from a scenario, this allow you to monitor progress or regression of your security posture on a given scenario.
**Simulation**: You will find here more granular information about a specific run, be able to track the progression of the simulation.
faq.question.executor_injectors_collecto: Executors run the actions, injectors define what to execute, and collectors gather results.
What are executors, injectors, and collectors?
faq.question.expectations_expire.details: Expectations expire if no collector reports results. Ensure a collector is deployed, or update the expectation manually.
faq.question.expectations_expire.summary: Why do my detection / prevention expectations always expire?
faq.question.get_help.details: OpenAEV is an open source projects, if you find bugs or you want to request a feature, feel free to open an issue in our [Github repository](https://github.com/OpenAEV-Platform/openaev/issues) & if you need support, reach us anytime on [Slack](https://app.slack.com/client/TJ1PH4GBZ).
faq.question.inject_missing_content.deta:
Missing content on an inject occurs when not all mandatory information are addressed, therefore the inject can’t be launch. 
In most cases, your injects is missing a target (an asset or a team) and in some cases it is missing a specific argument.
Edit your inject and provide the required content to run the inject smoothly.
faq.question.inject_missing_content.summ: My inject has the status "missing content", what does that mean?
faq.question.share_scenarios.details: Scenarios can be exported and imported through the platform. You can also fetch new scenarios from our [XTM Hub library](https://hub.filigran.io/cybersecurity-solutions/open-bas-scenarios).
faq.question.share_scenarios.summary: How can I share or reuse scenarios?
faq.question.simulations_production.deta: Simulations mimic real attacker behaviour and may impact services. Run in production only after impact evaluation and approval from your security team. You can always test first your scenario in a lab environment for safety.
faq.question.simulations_production.summ: Can I run simulations in production?

getting_started_description_conclusion_t: You will soon want to create new scenarios to test your security posture. When ready to do so, you can learn how we created a Scenario to simulate Salt Typhoon threat and test by yourself! OpenAEV is your toolbox!
getting_started_description_end_text: At the end of the Simulation, you will be able to consult results like vulnerable endpoints, found credentials, detection and prevention from integrated security solutions, and more!
getting_started_description_first_task_t: First task is to import an attack scenario that represent a threat you want to validate your Security Posture against. Below you will be able to leverage technical or tabletop scenario to begin with.
getting_started_description_scenario_tex: A Scenario must be launched. A Simulation will then be instantiated where you will be able to follow the progress of the emulated events (called injects!).
getting_started_description_text: The platform allows you to entirely create custom attack scenarios to emulate on endpoints. You can even create your own automated tabletop crisis simulation! Such potential can be daunting and hard to harness fully. So let’s get started with ready-to-use content to understand the global workflow of the platform and its values!
